    "markdown": "## CT Screening Shoulder Overview\n\n## Shoulder CT Scan at Cadabams Diagnostics | Fast, Accurate Imaging\n## Need a clear picture of that lingering shoulder pain? A \\*\\*CT screening shoulder scan\\*\\* at Cadabams Diagnostics creates high-resolution, 3-D images in minutes—pinpointing fractures, rotator-cuff injuries and arthritis so your doctor can plan the right care, fast.\n## What is a Shoulder CT Scan?\n## A \\*\\*shoulder CT scan\\*\\* (also called \\*\\*CT imaging of the shoulder joint\\*\\*) is a painless, non-invasive test that uses X-rays and computer processing to capture cross-sectional images of bones, joints and soft tissues in the shoulder region. At Cadabams Diagnostics, our 128-slice CT technology reconstructs these slices into a detailed 3-D model that doctors can rotate and examine from every angle—something ordinary X-rays simply can’t provide.\n## When to Take Test\nConsider a shoulder CT if you:\n- Have persistent shoulder pain that hasn’t improved with rest or physiotherapy\n- Suffered a fall, sports injury or accident and need to rule out \\*\\*scapula fracture CT scan\\*\\* findings\n- Experience clicking, locking or limited range of motion in the joint\n- Need a surgical plan for \\*\\*shoulder instability CT\\*\\* or \\*\\*rotator cuff CT scan\\*\\* evaluation Typical candidates include athletes, manual labourers, senior adults with osteoarthritis and post-surgery patients.\n\n## Risks & Limitations of the CT Screening Shoulder\n\n- \\*\\*Radiation exposure:\\*\\* Comparable to a few months of natural background radiation; well within safe limits.\n- \\*\\*Contrast allergies:\\*\\* Rare iodine reactions can occur with contrast-enhanced scans; inform staff about previous allergies.\n- \\*\\*Soft-tissue detail:\\*\\* While excellent for bone, subtle ligament or tendon injuries may still need an MRI.\n---\n## Types of Shoulder CT Scan\n| Scan Type | Purpose |\n|-----------|---------|\n| \\*\\*Non-contrast shoulder CT scan\\*\\* | Ideal for bones & calcified structures |\n| \\*\\*Contrast-enhanced shoulder CT scan\\*\\* | Highlights blood vessels, tumours or infections |\n| \\*\\*CT arthrography\\*\\* | Combines dye injection with CT for superior cartilage and labrum detail |\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During the CT Screening Shoulder\n\nOur radiologists evaluate:\n- \\*\\*Humeral head alignment\\*\\* with glenoid socket\n- \\*\\*Acromioclavicular joint space\\*\\* width\n- \\*\\*Glenoid bone loss\\*\\* for instability cases\n- \\*\\*Rotator-cuff footprint integrity\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Calcific deposits\\*\\* or \\*\\*bone spurs\\*\\*\n\n## Reasons for Taking a CT Screening Shoulder\n\n- Detect \\*\\*complex fractures\\*\\* invisible on X-ray\n- Assess \\*\\*shoulder dislocation\\*\\* and subsequent bone damage\n- Plan \\*\\*shoulder replacement surgery\\*\\*\n- Monitor healing after fracture fixation\n- Investigate chronic pain or unexplained swelling\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Test\n\n- \\*\\*15-minute scan time\\*\\* with same-day digital report\n- Sub-millimetre resolution for \\*\\*shoulder joint CT scan\\*\\* accuracy\n- Online report access via secure portal\n- Dedicated musculoskeletal radiologist interprets every study\n- Wheelchair-friendly facility and flexible appointment slots\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with CT Screening Shoulder\n\n- \\*\\*Rotator-cuff tears\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Shoulder fractures\\*\\* (humerus, scapula, clavicle)\n- \\*\\*Osteoarthritis & rheumatoid arthritis\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Frozen shoulder (adhesive capsulitis)\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Shoulder impingement syndrome\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Infections & bone tumours\\*\\*\n\n## Preparing for CT Screening Shoulder\n\n### Pre-requisites\n- Bring doctor’s prescription and valid ID\n- Remove jewellery, hairpins or metal objects near shoulders\n- Wear loose cotton clothing or change into our gown\n### Best Time to Take the Scan\nMorning appointments are ideal, especially if contrast dye is required—this allows more time to monitor for any mild reaction and gives you the rest of the day to resume normal activities.\n### Eligibility\n- Adults and children over 5 years\n- Pregnant women should consult their obstetrician first; we avoid radiation during the first trimester whenever possible\n---\n## Caution Before the Test\n- \\*\\*Diabetes medications:\\*\\* Metformin may need to be paused 48 hours after contrast; ask your doctor.\n- \\*\\*Kidney function:\\*\\* Recent creatinine report required if contrast is planned.\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia:\\*\\* Our open-bore CT reduces anxiety; sedation is rarely needed."
  },
